\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm we've described so far works for graded 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebras.
 We can extend the algorithm to all 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebras as follows: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(F,\star)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra which is finitely generated as a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-vector space with ordered basis 
\begin_inset Formula $(e_{0},e_{1},\dots,e_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 We define a graded 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{F}$
\end_inset

 as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{F}_{0} & =Ke_{0}\\
\widetilde{F}_{1} & =Ke_{1}+\cdots+Ke_{n}\\
\widetilde{F}_{2} & =Kte_{1}+\cdots+Kte_{n}\\
\widetilde{F}_{3} & =Kt^{2}e_{1}+\cdots+Kt^{2}e_{n}\\
 & \vdots\\
\widetilde{F}_{n} & =Kt^{n-1}e_{1}+\cdots+Kt^{n-2}e_{n}\\
 & \vdots
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The idea is that 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is an indeterminate which merely keeps track of the grading.
 Multiplication on 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{F}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t^{m}e_{i}\star t^{n}e_{j}:=t^{m+n}(e_{i}\star e_{j})
\]

\end_inset

and extended everywhere else linearly.
 
